                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17700425-27-off176 t17700425-27-cd158"></join>. My servant maid told me of it in the morning, about eight o'clock, before I was up. I found the shutters of the parlour window wrenched open; I imagine with a chissel, and the sash was lifted up, and the blind taken away. I missed a silver watch from the mantle-piece, and two coats out of the same room. It was one o'clock before I left that room to go to bed; all was safe then. I went and informed Sir John of my watch, and on the 5th of this instant Sir John sent for me: there I saw it again. I was sent with a constable to Golden-lane, to see for my other things. (The prisoner was then in custody). There were two women in the prisoner's house; we looked about, and found other things, but nothing belonging to me. We went up into the old woman, the mother's room, and, in a box, I found the chain of my watch. I went to the prisoner in Newgate last Tuesday, and said to him, if he had pawned my clothes I would be glad if he would let me know, that I might have them again: he said he had sold them to an old clothes man, and I could not have them again.</p>
